<section xml:id="sec-the-fundamental-theorem-of-calculus">
  <title>The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Relate accumulated area to antiderivatives through the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Evaluate definite integrals by subtracting antiderivative values at endpoints.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret indefinite integrals as families of antiderivatives.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Come back to the area of a circle?
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        FTC part I (Evaluation Theorem)
      </p>

      <p>
        If <m>f^{(-1)}</m> is an antiderivative of <m>f(x)</m>, then:
        <aside>
          <p>
            These more descriptive names for the two parts are due to Bill Kinney at Bethel University.
          </p>
        </aside>
        <me>
          \int_{a}^{b} f(x)\dd{x}=f^{(-1)}(b)-f^{(-1)}(a)
        </me>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        FTC part II (Antiderivative Construction Theorem):
      </p>

      <p>
        If <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>, then the function
        <me>
          \int_{c}^{x}f(t)\dd{t}
        </me>
        is an antiderivative of <m>f</m>, that is,
        <me>
          \dv{x}\int_{c}^{x} f(t)\dd{t}=f(x)
        </me>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Indefinite integral:
      </p>

      <p>
        If <m>f^{(-1)}</m> is an antiderivative of <m>f</m>, we define
        <me>
          \int f(x)\dd{x}=f^{(-1)}(x)+C
        </me>
        where <m>C</m> is an arbitrary constant.
        Hence the indefinite integral is the entire family of antiderivatives, all offset from each other by a constant.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Practice with antiderivatives, only using the Anti-Power Rule:
        <me>
          \int x^{n}\dd{x}=\frac{1}{n+1}x^{n+1}+C
        </me>
        (as long as <m>n\neq -1</m>)
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
